text: First off, to the people complaining that their are jump scares in the TRAILER, let me just say that you haven't seen the  movie yet so you can't just assume they will be in the film as well.   Secondly, I will admit, this trailer had a lot of "unnatural jump-scares," essentially, the noises accompanying the scares are from the musical score rather than an entity or object in the film's universe producing it's natural sound. The best use of a jump scare as of late was in Five Nights at Freddy's, where the sound came only from the animatronic voice box, which is something in the game's universe thus keeping the immersion in the game even with a rather cheap scare tactic. There is nothing wrong with a jump-scare if it is done naturally instead of mechanically.  However, I have a feeling that a lot of these jump-scare music tings have been purposefully inserted into the trailer to market the movie to more people as a way of getting them to see it. Ouija: Origin of Evil had it's trailers with some jump scares in them, but the movie itself contained none of the sort.    Finally, I am going to see this film no matter what. Whether their are cheap-o jump scares in the movie has, again, yet to be confirmed by anyone. If there are, I will pull no punches in bringing them up in a written review. For now, I suggest we all wait patiently till the movie's release.  Thank You.

text: The novel was really incredibly frightening when I read it when it first came out.  The TV movie in 1990, I thought, was very faithful to the book and frightened me the same way.  I don't know why they remade it into a feature film, when the two-part TV movie was so good.  I'm not a critic or cynic, I just don't understand why it's being remade again.  Is it because technology has changed so much to allow more "special effects"?  Or has Hollywood completely run out of imagination so they just remake what worked before?  (After all, think about it:  "Will and Grace" and "Roseanne" are both being "rebooted" for this fall.)

text: When I was a kid I was dumb enough to ask for my parents to let me see the original film that was being screened at a nearby cinema near my house, my parents agreed on the condition that an adult went with me (now I realize why they didn't want to go with me) so my godmother, her husband and two kids came along. I was around eleven at the time and you can imagine the kind of impression that it left me with, and it scared the hell out of my godmother and her family too, and we are still very uncomfortable around clowns.   When I heard that the movie was getting a reboot I though that since it has been such a long time since that day and that the fact that I'm much older now would watch this video and see if it would still make me nervous and goddamnit, that red headed psycho still gets under my skin.  I think this shows how great Stephen King is and that probably another generation will frightened by that monster that he created

text: My opinion on this movie differs quite a lot from all the other reviews I've seen in the comments; I didn't like the movie. It wasn't scary, therefore, classifying it in the "horror" genre is completely irrelevant. If the genre was comedy I'd actually give it a 9/10 rating, no joke, it was VERY funny, most of the time during the movie, the crowd were laughing their asses off. Actors did an amazing job, but I just fail to see how this movie got such high ratings and it wasn't even slightly horrific. Yes, creepy, but exclude all the lame jump scares and this movie would definitely go down the drain (huehue, pun intended). I'm not saying that if I don't like it you won't, I'm just stating my personal opinion; it's not worth your money.

text: Saw this movie last night it was cool to see it remade from the 90's version.  It wasn't as scary as I was expecting it to be though.   In my opinion they didn't quite get the true character and look of 'IT' right when comparing it to the book.  I just didn't believe watching it that Pennywise the clown was really truly evil.    Sure the clown drools and does creepy movements, but it would have been scarier if the clown was even more elusive.  It should have been played by an older man not a young one, with a deep voice and more 1800ish clothing.  Somehow Tim Currey as IT in the 90's version still scares me more, not sure why.   I wanted to see IT being more demonic in nature, and being that I've come against and battled real demons the things most people don't even know exist, I can say it wasn't entirely accurate.  The kids in the movie kind of related to IT as if he was some scary serial killer, but it would have added to the psychological viewers affect if for example; they fainted or were paralyzed in fear when confronted by the clown which is what happens in real life when your in the presence of a real evil demonic being.   Pennywise should have been less hands on with the kids, until the finale scene in the sewers, because by that point they all met IT face to face already. If the kids saw Pennywise from a distance throughout the movie, and had the psychological mind tricks played on them until the finale in the sewers it would have added a level of mystery to the big confrontation. That way it adds  to the scary anticipation of facing IT.    Sometimes less is more, and admittedly the 1990's 'IT' movie still creeps me out more even though its more simplistic with no affects, maybe its just Tim Currey who naturally looks evil.

text: Yes I saw it. I saw the 80's version, I saw 2017 and I read it .. obviously the book is the best. The 2017 was better than the 80's version but still it didn't scare me ... I think this movie would scare 16 and under.  I've seen and done too much to be afraid of this movie .. actually I haven't seen a movie in the past 20 years that could do that.  There is a formula and Hollywood follows it with slight variations here and there but it's still the same old formula.  I have to say though, when the movie industry tries to pass gratuitous gore for horror it's reaching. So overall I say I give this movie a 4 out of 10.   P.S. I felt like I was watching a cross between Freddy Krueger and the goonies on acid.

text: Im actually pretty shocked that this movie didn't *completely suck.*  Almost all movie remakes are just flat out *_AWFUL_* and are usually poorly and carelessly written.  You can tell that there was good effort put into this reboot. The writer/director obviously cared about what we, the audience, thought about it and whether or not we liked it. Ill admit, I had my serious doubts. Especially when i learned who was hired to play my    *_Pennywise the Dancing Clown_* but he actually did an amazing job! As did all of the kids. Phenomenal acting by all of them. I was damn impressed by their acting abilities at that age.  Now, I can't wait for the sequel!! It's going to be even better! Just please don't make them fight a freaking ginourmous spider, okay? I'm begging you.... *We are _ALLL_ begging you! No giant spider, period! K, thanks!   (PS. Anyone who's seen the original 1992 version of *'IT'* knows what I'm talking about and knows how awful it was and how much it really killled that movies ending.

text: I was skeptical prior to watching this film. I enjoyed the originals as a kid and although Hollywood has a track record for fudging up remakes I thought I would give it a chance. To be honest, it was hard to stomach. So much so that I would rather not watch part two. It did not feel genuine. It felt sloppy. False hearted acting and poor directing played a major part in that. A movie should not feel like it is one giant script molded into a spit wad. The outcome of this film was to expected in my opinion. Movie magic has been on a decline for years and it is a rarity for a good film to emerge nowadays.
